<section class="faq-section">
    <div class="faq-inner">
        <div class="faq-left">
            <p class="titan-section-label">COMMON QUESTIONS</p>
            <h2 class="faq-heading">Annuity FAQ</h2>
            <p class="faq-sub">Get straight answers about annuities from a fiduciary advisor.</p>
            <a href="/contact/" class="resources-cta">Schedule Annuity Review</a>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-right">
            <div class="faq-accordion">
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">What is a fixed index annuity?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">A fixed index annuity links returns to a stock market index (like the S&P 500) but protects your principal from losses. You get a portion of market gains (subject to caps and participation rates) but never lose money in down years. They're complex products with varying fees and features that should be carefully evaluated. Guarantees are subject to the claims-paying ability of the issuing insurance company.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">Are annuities a good investment?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Annuities aren't investments — they're insurance products designed to provide guaranteed income. They can be appropriate if you need income protection and don't have a pension, but they often come with high fees, limited liquidity, and surrender charges. The key is determining if the guaranteed income feature is worth the trade-offs for your specific situation.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">What fees do annuities have?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Annuity fees vary widely. Variable annuities typically charge 2-3% annually (mortality and expense charges, investment fees, rider fees). Fixed and fixed index annuities may have lower annual fees but often include surrender charges (penalties for early withdrawal) that can last 5-10 years. We help you understand the total cost structure before you commit.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">Can I get out of an annuity?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Yes, but it may be expensive. Most annuities have surrender charges that decrease over time (often 5-10 years). You may also owe taxes and IRS penalties if you're under 59½. We review your existing annuity to determine if it makes sense to exit, stay in, or modify it through available options like 1035 exchanges.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">When does an annuity make sense?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Annuities can make sense if you need guaranteed lifetime income and don't have a pension, want to transfer longevity risk to an insurance company, or need a simple income solution in retirement. They typically DON'T make sense if you need liquidity, have low risk tolerance but high fees, or already have sufficient guaranteed income from Social Security and pensions. Every situation is different — we analyze yours specifically.</div>
                </button>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
